Univariate Analysis

We can conclude from the above histogram that most contributions are for $25, $100 followed by $250. Few people made contributions above $250.

Above histogram shows that Barack Obama received significantly more number of contributions than any other candidate. Next highest number of contributions were received by Hillary Clinton.

Democrats received at least 8 times more number of contributions than republicans in the state of WA. WA is typically a liberal state, so the data is not surprising.

Number of Contributions from both males and females is almost equal

This is a negatively skewed distribution indicating most contributions came as the general election was getting close. In 2007 when candidates declared their intent to run, they started receiving contributions but in low numbers. Significant number of contributions came after primaries and national conventions are done.

What is the structure of your dataset?

WA state 2008 election contributions dataset contains 130353 observations and 12 variables. Other observations: -Most contributions went to Democrats -Median donation is $25 -Almost equal number of males and females donated to 2008 elections in WA state. -Males donated a total of $13 million + -Females donated a total of $9 million+ -Democrats received 115,000 + contributions -Republicans received 14,000 + contributions

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?

Main features of interest for analysis is the size and number of contributions. Number of contributions received by party Number of contributions received by each candidate ### What other features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?

Zipcodes impact on contributions Gender impact on contributions ### Did you create any new variables from existing variables in the dataset?

I created two new variables in the dataset. party - Candidate name is used to identify party for each record. This will help to analyze contributions by party. gender - I split the contributors name into first name and last name. With the help of gender package and utilizing the first name, I predicted the contributors gender. This will help to analyze gender influence on the contributions and support for a candidate.

Create a linear regression model to predict contribution amounts

m1 = lm(contb_receipt_amt ~ cand_nm + gender + contbr_zip , data=wa) R-squared is 0.069 and it doesnt seem to be a very strong model. Given that contribution amounts vary a lot, it is very hard to predict it using a simple linear model. This is the best linear model that is possible for this data.

Reflection

The 2008 election contribution data set for WA state contains 147149 observations and 18 variables. I reviewed the summary of the dataset and removed refunds and reattributions to eliminate double counting. I also removed the columns that are not helpful for the analysis to reduce the size of the dataset. Then I chose to add couple of columns (gender and party) to help with the analysis. I further removed the records for the candidates who received less than 500 contributions. The final dataset I used for analysis contained 130260 observations and 13 variables.

Since WA State leans toward democrats, I was expecting to see higher contributions for democrats. However, the analysis showed that mean contribution amount is higher for republicans. But the number of contributions received by democrats is way higher than republicans, which is expected. Also Barack Obama received $15million in total contributions compared to $2.5 million for John McCain. I was surprised to see such a significant difference between the final two candidates. Also it was good to see both females and males showed equal enthusiasm in their participation in election contributions.

I created a linear model to predict contribution amounts based on the variables gender, zipcode and candidate name. It turned out that it is a weak model with R-squared 0.069. I expected adding Party will improve the model, but didnt make a difference. Given that contribution amounts vary a lot, it will be very hard to predict it with a simple linear model. A different type of model should be considered in the future. Further analysis can be done based on contributors occupation, but the data will need lot of clean up before analysis.
